00:05:04,720 --> 00:05:12,320
Now most people think that the questions are so that you as the app maker get to know more about your users.

75
00:05:12,320 --> 00:05:13,520
But that's not the case at all.

76
00:05:13,520 --> 00:05:20,160
What you absolutely want to do is to make the users convince themselves that this is an app that they need.

77
00:05:20,160 --> 00:05:25,199
In Prairie Lock's case, again, we just ask very personal questions that we already know the users struggle with,

78
00:05:25,199 --> 00:05:26,479
like thinking bigger.

79
00:05:26,479 --> 00:05:28,400
What does a thriving face look like to you?

80
00:05:28,400 --> 00:05:30,560
And each answer choice is very deliberate.

81
00:05:30,560 --> 00:05:37,039
The fourth principle of the introduction is that you need to reflect the users's answers back at them.

82
00:05:37,039 --> 00:05:40,880
If in your onboarding you ask a question about social media addiction and they tell you,

83
00:05:40,880 --> 00:05:43,199
"Yes, I have social media addiction."

84
00:05:43,199 --> 00:05:47,280
In the next screen, you would say, "Hey, we see that you have social media addiction."

85
00:05:47,280 --> 00:05:50,960
So, in prayer lock's case, we ask them, "What do you want to achieve with prayer lock?"

86
00:05:50,960 --> 00:05:54,880
They say, "I want to put God first before my phone, build consistent prayer habit, etc."

87
00:05:54,880 --> 00:05:57,840
We just pit those same answers right back at them in the next screen.

88
00:05:57,840 --> 00:06:05,120
And this sounds silly, but what this does is makes the user feel heard, makes the user feel like this is going to be a personalized experience for them.

89
00:06:05,120 --> 00:06:08,479
And then something to keep in mind, longer onboardings will do better.

90
00:06:08,479 --> 00:06:16,080
In Perilock's old onboarding, we had only around 20 screens and our conversion rate with free trial was around 3%.

91
00:06:16,080 --> 00:06:21,199
When we updated the onboarding to be more than 10 to 15 minutes long, depending on the user,

92
00:06:21,199 --> 00:06:24,240
our conversion rate 5xed to 15%.

93
00:06:24,240 --> 00:06:28,000
The reason this happens is because of something called loss aversion.

94
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:32,479
And people in general would rather not lose than win something.

95
00:06:32,479 --> 00:06:37,199
So by the time they get to the pay wall, they're thinking,"Hey, I already invested 10 minutes,

